<h2>Iowa Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Iowa offers several attractive incentive programs that make solar and HVAC investments more affordable and financially attractive for homeowners. Understanding and properly utilizing these incentives can significantly reduce project costs and improve return on investment.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The federal government provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the full cost of solar equipment and installation, including permits and electrical work. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this credit provides \$6,000 in tax savings. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability, and there is no income cap or maximum credit amount.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption for Renewable Energy:</strong> Iowa provides a complete property tax exemption for solar energy systems and other renewable energy installations. This means the added value of solar panels to your home assessment is exempt from property taxation, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime. For a typical solar installation adding \$15,000-20,000 in home value, this can save \$300-500 annually in property taxes.</li>

<li><strong>MidAmerican Energy Rebates:</strong> MidAmerican Energy offers various rebate programs for energy efficiency upgrades, including up to \$500 for high-efficiency heat pumps, \$400 for ENERGY STAR certified air conditioners, and up to \$200 for smart thermostats. The utility also provides free energy audits and additional rebates for comprehensive home efficiency improvements. Their EnergyAdvantage program can provide rebates of up to \$1,500 for geothermal heat pump installations.</li>

<li><strong>Net Metering:</strong> Iowa's net metering policy allows solar customers to receive credit for excess electricity produced by their systems. MidAmerican Energy and most Iowa utilities provide net metering, typically crediting excess production at the retail electricity rate. This effectively allows your electric meter to run backward during peak production periods, maximizing the value of solar generation.</li>

<li><strong>Rural Energy for America Program (REAP):</strong> Rural Iowa residents and agricultural operations may qualify for USDA REAP grants and loan guarantees covering up to 25% of renewable energy project costs. This federal program can be combined with other incentives and is particularly valuable for larger installations or agricultural applications.</li>
</ul>

